  "prompt": "When were cotton fibres first used?",
  "response": "Cotton fibers have been used by humans for thousands of years. The earliest evidence of cotton use dates back to around **5000 BCE** in the Indus Valley Civilization, in what is now modern-day Pakistan and northwest India. Archaeological findings, such as cotton fabric remnants and cotton seeds, suggest that cotton was cultivated and spun into textiles during this time.\n\nCotton was also independently cultivated and used in other parts of the world, including:\n- **Mexico and Peru** (around 3000 BCE): Evidence of cotton use in the Americas has been found in archaeological sites.\n- **The Middle East** (around 3000 BCE): Cotton was introduced to regions like Mesopotamia and Egypt.\n\nBy the time of the **Renaissance**, cotton had spread to Europe, and it became a globally traded commodity during the **Industrial Revolution**, transforming textile production. Today, cotton remains one of the most widely used natural fibers in the world.",
